  "prompt": "Does Java support Multiple Inheritance?",
  "response": "No, Java does not support multiple inheritance for classes. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. Multiple Inheritance in Classes:\n```java\n// This is NOT allowed in Java\nclass A {}\nclass B {}\nclass C extends A, B {}  // Compilation Error!\n```\n\n2. Single Inheritance for Classes:\n```java\n// Only single inheritance is supported for classes\nclass A {}\nclass B extends A {}  // This is valid\n```\n\n3. Interface Multiple Inheritance:\n```java\n// Interfaces CAN have multiple inheritance\ninterface A {}\ninterface B {}\ninterface C extends A, B {}  // This is allowed\n```\n\n4. Alternatives to Multiple Inheritance:\n   - Use interfaces\n   - Use composition\n   - Use default methods in interfaces (Java 8+)\n\nExample of interface multiple inheritance:\n```java\ninterface Flyable {\n    void fly();\n}\n\ninterface Swimmable {\n    void swim();\n}\n\ninterface Bird extends Flyable, Swimmable {\n    void chirp();\n}\n```\n\nReasons Java doesn't support multiple inheritance for classes:\n- Avoid complexity of diamond problem\n- Simplify class hierarchy\n- Prevent ambiguity in method resolution\n\nSo while Java doesn't support multiple inheritance for classes, it provides other mechanisms to achieve similar functionality.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
